{"id":"1904.03789","submitter":"Alexei Zhedanov","authors":"Alexei Zhedanov","title":"Classical Sturmian sequences","comments":"14 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Sturm sequence is generated by a pair of polynomials $P(x)$ and $P'(x)$,\nwhere $P(x)$ is assumed to have simple real roots. Euclidean algorithm\ngenerates then a finite sequence of polynomials orthogonal on the grid $x_s$ of\nroots of the polynomial $P(x)$. This algorithm can be exploited in order to\nfind the number of roots of the polynomial $P(x)$ inside a given interval. We\nconsider the \"inverse\" problem: what is the explicit system of orthogonal\npolynomials generated by the prescribed grid $x_s$ of \"classical\" type. The\nmain results are the following. The generic linear grid generates a special\ncase of the Hahn polynomials. The quadratic grids $x_s=x(s+1)$ and $x_s=s(s+2)$\ncorrespond to two special cases of the Racah polynomials. The generic\nexponential grid is related to a special case of the q-Hahn polynomials.\nFinally, we show that two special trigonometric grids are related to the\nChebyshev polynomials of the first and second kind.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 Apr 2019 01:05:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-09"}
